{
  "texts": [
    "However, the semantics of DAGs are not detailed enough to represent this information.",
    "Figure 11a illustrates this issue using a causal graph of four observed variables {A, B, C, D}, and a latent confounder L which would entail the dependence rela- tionships A ⟂ D|B, A ⟂ D|C, and A ̸ ⟂ D|B, C.",
    "If we attempt to represent this with a DAG of just the four observable variables, then there is no orientation of a directed edge between B and C that could entail these dependence relationships.",
    "Figure 11b presents an ancestral graph which, unlike DAGs, captures relationships due to latent confounders, and which we describe in the subsection that follows below.",
    "Richardson and Spirtes (2002) introduced a new class of graph called an ancestral graph 4 capable of capturing the relationships between observed variables in the presence of both latent confounders and selection bias."
  ]
}